<br>
<br>
<DIV class="poemtitle">Pitching Poetry</DIV><br>
  <div align="center"><img src="images/pitchingpoetry.jpg"><br>
  <a class="artistline" href="javascript:goauthor('jones');">art by Pat Jones</a></div><br>
<TABLE><TR><TD>
<br><br>
<p style="font-size:80%"><i>Just when I think my office is under attack<br /> by a horde of iambic zombies, I get a sonnet<br /> or villanelle that reminds me of everything those<br /> old forms can do.</i><br />
&#8212;Christian Wiman, Editor, Poetry, November 2003</p><br /><br />

Scene One: we open in a crypt,<br />
Van Helsing and this babe, equipped<br />
<br />
With flickering torches, lights that play<br />
Along these rows of . . . what're they?<br />
<br />
Books. <i>Jesus Christ</i>, he says, <i>I fear<br />
They're gnawing on these dead. Look, here.</i><br />
<br />
Cut to her feet. <i>You're one of them!</i><br />
There's couplets dripping from her hem.<br />
<br />
Pan up (we'll use a shaky-cam)<br />
And she can only croak, <i>Iamb!</i> <br /><br>
<br /><hr>
Previously published in <i>Folly</i>
<br><br>
<a class="byline" href="javascript:goauthor('osen')">by Frank Osen</a><br><br><br>
</TD></TR></TABLE>
